nd its role in tests. The existing project tests use a catch for direct classloader, but there's a note to avoid this pattern for things like reflection or serialization — those tests should run under Native Image. This specific test involves dynamic class loading, but the class isn't discovered post-build. I wonder if removing the catch would ensure that Native runs, yet the KotlinCoreEnvironment could fail due to unsupported dynamic loading. The TCK native image classloader can still load classes by name, so maybe we shouldn't catch at all?\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Removing the catch**\\\\n\\\\nI see that the instructions don't always mandate using a catch, so I’m considering removing it to better align with best practices. The existing tests import NativeImageSupport, which may not be necessary, but I wonder if removing it could lead to failure. KotlinCoreEnvironment might be used in native, but I’m not sure if the native image supports all compiler functionality. Ideally, tests need to run under Native by default, and if the dynamic access point is `ClassLoader#loadClass`, generating metadata could help avoid issues with missing coverage.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring Kotlin support dynamics**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering if the native environment can support the Kotlin compiler. If not, maybe using catch could work due to dynamic class loading? I need to focus on that target call, which is all about dynamic class loading. Hmm, it might be helpful to check the test-results-native to see if they currently all pass. This could guide my next steps in figuring out what to do.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_c2Oqco6ZcSGGwVAldGq9SjZ3|fc_0e284eda8ac4086b0169fb758e218481a394765b79b76f2f86\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"find tests/src/org.jetbrains.kotlin/kotlin-scripting-compiler-impl-embeddable/2.3.21/test-results-native -type f -maxdepth 4 | head -10\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 1461, \"output\": 794, \"cacheRead\": 32768, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 35023, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1778087293069, \"responseId\": \"resp_0e284eda8ac4086b0169fb757de5d881a38858eb92c48e066f\"}}\n7088:+[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering Kotlin import issues**\\n\\nI’m exploring the need for import ordering in Kotlin, considering uses like ktlint. An existing file arranges imports alphabetically with Java first, then Kotlin, and finally org. However, a new file is starting with Kotlin and org, omitting Java. There's a potential issue with a top-level annotation class not named Test, but it seems public — so that’s acceptable. Each dynamic-access class should keep its own Kotlin test file for coverage, but there's a concern about how a catch might swallow errors.\\n\\n**Examining dynamic class loading**\\n\\nI'm thinking about dynamic class loading and its role in tests. The existing project tests use a catch for direct classloader, but there's a note to avoid this pattern for things like reflection or serialization — those tests should run under Native Image. This specific test involves dynamic class loading, but the class isn't discovered post-build. I wonder if removing the catch would ensure that Native runs, yet the KotlinCoreEnvironment could fail due to unsupported dynamic loading. The TCK native image classloader can still load classes by name, so maybe we shouldn't catch at all?\\n\\n**Removing the catch**\\n\\nI see that the instructions don't always mandate using a catch, so I’m considering removing it to better align with best practices. The existing tests import NativeImageSupport, which may not be necessary, but I wonder if removing 